## 2. Architecture Overview

```
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│                 Consuming Microservice                  │
│                                                         │
│   @SpringBootApplication                                │
│   @EnableCommon             ──► Core Utils               │
│   @EnableCustomSecurity     ──► JWT + Auth Filters       │
│   @EnableEncryption         ──► RSA Service              │
│   @EnableCache              ──► Ehcache / InMemory       │
│   @EnableNotifications      ──► RabbitMQ Publisher        │
│   @EnableFreeMarker         ──► Template Rendering        │
│                                                         │
└──────────────────────┬──────────────────────────────────┘
                       │
                       ▼
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│                    common-lib (JAR)                      │
│                                                         │
│   com.itways.annotation    ← Enable annotations          │
│   com.itways.common        ← Responses, Exceptions, DTOs │
│   com.itways.security      ← JWT, Filters, AccountId     │
│   com.itways.encryption    ← RSA encrypt/decrypt         │
│   com.itways.cache         ← Cache abstraction layer     │
│   com.itways.notification  ← RabbitMQ messaging          │
│   com.itways.freemarker    ← Template engine             │
│                                                         │
└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
```

**How the `@Enable*` pattern works under the hood:**

Each annotation uses Spring's `@Import` to pull in a `@Configuration` class.
That configuration class uses `@ComponentScan` to register all beans in its package.

```
@EnableCommon
    └── @Import(CommonConfig.class)
            └── @ComponentScan("com.itways.common")
                    → GlobalExceptionHandler, CustomErrorController, SwaggerConfig, etc.
```

> **Important:** `@EnableCustomSecurity` *automatically* includes `@EnableCache` (because JWT replay protection and security context rely on caching). So if you enable security, caching comes for free.

