## 6. Known Issues & Technical Debt

| # | Item | Severity | Details |
|---|---|---|---|
| 1 | **`SecurityUtils` uses static methods with Spring-injected key** | ⚠️ Medium | The AES encryption key is injected via `@Value` into a static field. If any code calls `SecurityUtils.encrypt()` before the Spring context is ready, it crashes. A non-static design would be safer. |
| 2 | **`RsaService` reuses JWT RSA keys** | ⚠️ Medium | Both `JwtTokenProvider` and `RsaService` read from `jwt.rsa.private-key` / `jwt.rsa.public-key`. This couples JWT signing and data encryption to the same key pair. Ideally, these should be separate key pairs (e.g., `rsa.data.private-key`). |
| 3 | **Encrypt-side chunking not implemented** | ⚠️ Low | `RsaService.decrypt()` handles `|`-delimited chunks, but `encrypt()` does not chunk large payloads. The assumption is that the frontend handles chunking. |
| 4 | **No unit tests** | 🔴 High | The `src/test` directory is empty. No test coverage for any module. |
| 5 | **`System.out.println` in `JwtTokenProvider`** | ⚠️ Low | Debug key generation uses `System.out.println` instead of the logger. |
| 6 | **Duplicate class name `CacheConfig`** | ⚠️ Low | Both `com.itways.cache.CacheConfig` (the DTO) and `com.itways.cache.config.CacheConfig` (the Spring config) share the same simple name. This can cause import confusion. |
| 7 | **Validation handler misuses `ApiResponse.success()`** | ⚠️ Low | `GlobalExceptionHandler.handleValidationExceptions()` creates a response via `ApiResponse.success()` and then manually sets status to `"error"`. Should use `ApiResponse.error()` or a dedicated factory method. |
| 8 | **`MemoryStore` has lazy expiration only** | ⚠️ Low | Expired entries are only cleaned up on access (`get`/`containsKey`). There's no background cleanup thread, so memory can accumulate stale entries. |

