## 7. Quick Mental Model

Think of `common-lib` like a **toolbox** that every microservice opens at startup:

```
YOU'RE BUILDING A NEW MICROSERVICE?
                │
                ▼
     Add common-lib dependency
                │
                ▼
     Annotate your main class:
     ┌──────────────────────────────────────┐
     │ @EnableCommon          (ALWAYS)       │ ← API responses, error handling, swagger
     │ @EnableCustomSecurity  (if authed)    │ ← JWT filter, @AccountId, API keys
     │ @EnableEncryption      (if sensitive)  │ ← RSA encrypt/decrypt
     │ @EnableCache           (if caching)    │ ← Ehcache or in-memory
     │ @EnableNotifications   (if messaging)  │ ← Publish to RabbitMQ
     │ @EnableFreeMarker      (if templates)  │ ← Render email templates
     └──────────────────────────────────────┘
                │
                ▼
     Add required properties to application.properties
                │
                ▼
     Done! All the utilities are auto-injected.
     Just @Autowire what you need.
```

**The two encryption systems (don't mix them up):**

| System | Class | Algorithm | Used For |
|---|---|---|---|
| **AES** | `SecurityUtils` | AES-ECB | Short values — account IDs embedded in JWT claims and API keys |
| **RSA** | `RsaService` (`EncryptionService`) | RSA-PKCS1 | Data at rest — passwords, PII, sensitive payloads from frontend |

**The two authentication paths:**

```
HTTP Request
    │
    ├── Has "Authorization: Bearer <jwt>" header?
    │       └── JwtAuthenticationFilter → validate JWT → set SecurityContext
    │
    └── Has "X-API-KEY: sk_live_..." header?
            └── ApiKeyAuthenticationFilter → parse/decrypt key → set SecurityContext
```

Both filters set the same `SecurityContext` shape, so downstream code (including `@AccountId`) works identically regardless of auth method.

